## 窶鬼tory Analysis: The Psychology of the Sky

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/da14493b-0acb-47c3-85c8-9d5508cb101f/1000014966.png)

The most fascinating part of Chapter 1182 isn't the fight窶琶t's the explanation of why the Celestial Dragons fear rain. Kilingham窶冱 monologue is chilling. Because they live in Mary Geoise, high above the clouds, they never experience weather. To them, rain isn't life-giving; it窶冱 an anomaly. It窶冱 an "apocalypse from the sky."

窶軌da is genius for this. He窶冱 humanizing their villainy by grounding it in a primal, ignorant fear. They wear those glass domes (the "fishbowls") not just for "purity," but as a psychological barrier against the "Rain Goddess" they were told stories about as children. It connects so beautifully back to Alabasta. Remember the Dance Powder? The "rhythm" of the rain? We now know that Zaza moves to that same rhythm.

窶亀his also fuels the theories about Monkey D. Dragon. If the World Government窶冱 greatest fear is the "Rain God" who can raise the sea levels, and Dragon has weather-manipulation powers, it finally explains why he is the "Most Wanted Man." He represents the literal existential dread of the World Nobles.

窶亀he confirmation of Ragnir窶冱 fruit also clears up some long-standing confusion. We窶况e seen objects "eat" fruits before (like Funkfreed), but a Mythical Zoan hammer that allows for ice/lightning manipulation is a whole new level of power-scaling. It makes Loki a legitimate threat to the top tiers.

